node.text:
Time for another #mansardmonday goodie! 💫 Posted @withregram • @therowhousecity Wissahickon Mansard Monday.
A brief history of the Wissahickon Neighborhood
: 
The village of Wissahickon was founded by officials of the Pencoyd Iron Works in the late nineteenth century.Beginning in the 1880s, growing numbers of mill owners and wealthy business owners from neighboring Manayunk sought elegant homes on ample lots; they set their eyes on land previously owned by prominent Philadelphia families -- including the Camac, Dobson, Salaignac, and Wetherill families -- along the Wissahickon Creek. Grand single-detached and semi-detached homes with ample side and rear yards were built, creating "a unique park side Victorian wonderland." The neighborhood was considered a highly desirable place to live as it had proximity to the Wissahickon Valley, tree-lined streets, new sewers and water services, and grand homes in high Victorian styling.

Happy #mansardmonday everyone! This house is a personal fave of ours. ❤️ Posted @withregram • @jdjudah The Morris Butler House, a Second Empire style house, was built for John Morris, an Indianapolis businessman in 1864. Morris lived there until 1870 when, because of financial difficulties, he sold the house to Noble  Chase Butler, a bankruptcy lawyer.
It is now on the National Register of Historic Places and used as an event venue.

node.text:
Sunday Funday ☀️
Pristine! Love seeing every details so clearly. Thanks for all of the history details too! Thanks for tagging #archi_ologie 
#Repost - @roamgalveston by @get_regrammer
Another weekend, another Galveston feature, another mansard-like roof? If you look close enough on the island, you can find a few more mansards than you may think.
•
For today’s Storm Survivor Sunday, we are back in the heart of the Great Fire of 1885 destruction zone. Similar to events following the Great Storm of 1900, builders and investors rushed to be the first on the ground to purchase and rebuild. William Pautsch, a contractor and carpenter born in Germany, purchased this lot in 1885 and built this square raised cottage right up against the sidewalk in 1886. Many years later, the home was moved further back on the lot.
•
Like many other homes in this area were used for tenants after the fire, this home housed many Galvestonians throughout the years. One such Galvestonian was Marino Scaperlenda, proprietor of one of Galveston’s most famous restaurants, Pickwick!
•

node.text:
“Why not??” Wednesday feature! The details on this are just gorgeous! 🤩 Be sure to swipe for a view of the stairway windows! 💘 Thanks for tagging #archi_ologie Posted @withregram • @godzilla1950 At 470 E Chicago St…another unique Stick Style house of Elgin. This one was completed in 1887 for stone cutter Arwin E. Price. Aside from being a successful businessman, owning a marble & granite works, Price pursued a political career as well, becoming mayor of Elgin in 1889. He would run for that office off /on for the next 30 yrs well into the early 1920’s. Price was dubbed the “Drunken Mayor” not for having a drinking problem, but for his highly entertaining political antics during his career. Sounds like he would be a perfect fit just for today’s political arena! 😉

The Price house is such a delightful example of that style. Charming details abound on it. I love the gazebo style downstairs porch and the dazzling woodwork of the upstairs porch! Plus the staircase stained glass windows are a sweet touch. Great paint job as well, but I yearn to see a touch of a contrasting warm color for more visual effect. The 2,400 sq ft house is still privately owned. #stickstylearchitecture #stickstyle #stickstylehouses #victorian #victorianhouse #victorianarchitecture #victorianstyle #archi  #archilovers #archilove #archidaily #housestalker #houseaddict #oldhouselove #curbappeal #stainedglass #oldhouseenthusiast #iloveoldhouses #thisoldhouse  #historichouse #houseportrait  #beautifulhouseoldandnew #houses_phototrip #arkitektur #oldhousecharm  #houseoftheday

#mansardmonday  The prettiest green home with that beautiful #mansardtower 
#Repost - @jdjudah by @get_regrammer
Acorn Hall was built by whiskey distiller, William Squibb in 1883. The architect included both Romanesque and Italianate elements. The house became dilapidated, and faced foreclosure but @indianalandmarks helped  new owners aquire the property who restored it to its original grandeur.
